text_blocks.snippet: TTS stands for Thrombosis with Thrombocytopenia Syndrome. It's a rare but serious condition where blood clots (thrombosis) form in unusual places, often alongside a low platelet count (thrombocytopenia). It has been linked to certain vaccines, specifically those for COVID-19, and is sometimes referred to as vaccine-induced immune thrombotic thrombocytopenia (VITT) or vaccine-induced prothrombotic immune thrombocytopenia.

list.snippet: Unusual clot formation: Blood clots occur in locations where they are not typically found, such as in veins of the brain or abdomen.
Low platelet count: This can make it harder for the blood to clot properly.
Possible link to vaccines: Certain vaccines, particularly mRNA COVID-19 vaccines, have been associated with TTS.

list.title: Diagnosis:
list.snippet: TTS is diagnosed through blood tests and scans (like CT scans) to identify the clots and low platelet count.

list.title: Treatment:
list.snippet: Treatment typically includes anticoagulant (anti-clotting) medications (excluding heparin), intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG), and high-dose steroids.
